Glass does not change the speed of light.  It slows down the trasmission of light, which is a vast distinction.<br>
<br>
Ex.<br>
There is a beam of light just crusing along through a vacuum at 'c' minding its own damned business.  Then comes along material x.  For all intents and purposes, material x can be a pool of water, a sheet of glass, an atmosphere of air, it really doesn't matter.  There is nothing that material x can do to that beam of light to make it stop crusing along at 'c,' or is there?<br>
<br>
Well, material x decides that it is going to put itself in front of the beam of light, just to see what's up.  So Mr. Beam Of Light hits the first atom of material x and disappears.  Guess what happen.  No, guess.  He was absorbed by the quantum states of the orbiting electrons.  Unfortunately for Mr. Material X, atoms can only do this for a brief amount of time.  That amount of time is dependent on how much energy it would take to push that electron up to the next quantum state.<br>
<br>
Anyway, since the atom can only hold that beam of light (or photon) for so long, it finally lets it go.  But DAMN, right there is another atom.  Again and again Mr. Beam Of Light runs into these atoms that chew up and spit out photons.  HOWEVER, the speed that Mr. Beam Of Light travels from one atom to the next is ALWAYS 'c.'  Go-friggin'-figure.<br>
<br>
The lesson:  Materials do NOT slow down the speed of light, only the transmission of light. <p><br>
